# Documentation Standards

## Markdown Documentation

- All documentation files use **Markdown syntax** (`.md` extension)
- Documentation is written in **English by default**
- Use clear, descriptive headings with proper hierarchy
- Use code blocks with language tags for code examples
- Use tables for structured data when appropriate

## Link Style

- **Prefer reference-style links** over inline links
- Collect all link references at the end of the document
- Use descriptive link text that makes sense without the URL

### Reference-Style Links (Preferred)

```markdown
See the [project documentation][docs] for more details.

[docs]: docs/README.md
```

### Inline Links (Avoid)

```markdown
See the [project documentation](docs/README.md) for more details.
```

### Benefits of Reference-Style Links

1. **Readability**: The document body is cleaner and easier to read
2. **Maintainability**: URLs are centralized at the end, easier to update
3. **Consistency**: All links follow the same pattern
4. **Reusability**: Link references can be reused multiple times

### Example Document Structure

```markdown
# Document Title

## Section 1

See the [project overview][overview] and [coding standards][standards].

## Section 2

For more information, check the [API documentation][api].

[//]: #Document-and-image-references

[overview]: docs/OVERVIEW.md
[standards]: .cursor/rules/coding-standards.mdc
[api]: docs/API.md
```

## Code Documentation

- XML documentation for code (classes, methods, properties) follows the rules in `coding-standards.mdc`
- Markdown documentation for project-level documentation (README, guides, etc.)
- Both should be written in English

## File Organization

- Project documentation in `docs/` folder
- Rules and standards in `.cursor/rules/` folder
- README files at project root and in major subdirectories

